body_text.text:
We would like to congratulate Yu et al. [
1
] for the well-written article that evaluated 64 tear samples from 17 COVID-19 patients and found that all tear samples tested negative for SARS-CoV-2, even for the one patient with ocular symptoms. They obtained a meaningful conclusion that the risk of ocular transmission of COVID-19 is low.

We applaud the authors for a major endeavor. However, we have different views on the role the ocular surface plays in COVID-19 transmission. Several potential limitations are worth discussing. First, the authors used a Schirmer’s strip to collect tears, which may not be reliable enough to test SARS-CoV-2. Although the Schirmer’s strip was previously validated in testing HSV-1 from tears [
2
], no evidence shows it also works for SARS-CoV-2. In recent studies in China [
3
]
[
4
], a conjunctival swab technique was used, and it obtained positive results. The authors only collected tears and may have missed the virus attached to the epithelium of the ocular surface or in conjunctival secretion, which may have led to incomplete results. Second, RT-PCR may not be sensitive enough to detect small quantities of SARS-CoV-2 RNA. Therefore, negative test results may be false negatives and cannot exclude the presence of the virus. Multiple specimens are needed to increase the sensitivity. Finally, even if the Schirmer’s strip and RT-PCR tests were highly accurate, it still cannot be concluded that transmission through tears is likely to be low. We think that two possible explanations can account for this. One is that the COVID-19 infection above the ocular surface may not express SARS-CoV-2 in the tears, or the concentration of SARS-CoV-2 may be low. The other is that the authors may have missed the window, as the viral shedding in ocular tissue may only last for a short period. The authors did not mention the exact time of testing. Xia et al. [
3
] detected positive conjunctival swab samples at three days after the course of the disease, when the patient had no severe fever or respiratory symptoms. Due to these limitations, the negative results must be interpreted with caution.
